It is 100% German manufactured and proofmarked, was imported by Interarms, and has a date code on the frame of "KI", which is 1998 manufacture.  The slide has a factory finish called "QPQ", which stands for "quench, polish, quench".  It is basically a hard, highly corrosion-resistant Tenifer finish (similar to Glock) that is not phosphated over, which gives it an appearance similar to a matte-finish hard chrome.  Not many Walthers were made with this finish and if you do some research, you'll see that it's quite desirable among Walther enthusiasts.  I purchased this pistol secondhand in 2005, added the night sights, and function-tested it with a couple hundred rounds of various FMJ and hollowpoints.  It was extremely accurate and 100% reliable, just as all of my other P99 pistols were.  I thoroughly cleaned the pistol, lubed it, and stored it.  As you can see, it is in exceptional condition and is very close to new.  The pistol comes with (2) 16rd factory mags, the original case, factory test target, original sights, extra back straps, and owner's manual.  FYI, the 16rd Walther P99 mags are very difficult to find and were what the pistol was originally designed for...however at some point and for some reason, Walther changed the standard mags to 15rds.  

I can text or email additional high-quality photos if you're interested.  Just let me know.

I'm asking $700 face-to-face in the north Dallas area.  If interested, you can either reply to this ad or text me at REDACTED.

title: For Sale/Trade:  MAS MLE 1949/56 with Grenade Launcher in 7.5x54
postcontent: For sale/trade beautiful example of an under appreciated French battle rifle.  This robust and reliable tilting bolt semiautomatic rifle chambered for the powerful 7.5x54 French is basically the French equivalent to the FAL.  Rifle comes complete with original MAS rubber bad dated 1962, 10 round detachable box magazine, iron sights adjustable for 1,200 meters plus flip up grenade launcher sights. The weapon is a G series rifle dating the receiver between 1958-1960 rifle has two armory refurbishment marks one from 1971 and one from 1981.  Barrel is dated 1976 meaning it was replaced the second time it was refurbished making it very likely that a round has never been fired through it.  All numbers match except the bolt which is also matching G series.  Comes with black steel replacement cocking knob plus the original French military white plastic cocking knob completly intact which is quite rare.  Only 275,000 of these rifles were ever built, most of which were simply destroyed after the French deemed them too worn out to serve.  Out of the few of these rifles that made it in to the U.S. before reserves of these rifles ran dry forever, most of them were converted to .308 by Century who did such a bad job converting the rifles most of the converted rifles are considered unsafe to fire.  This is a rare example of a rifle that was left in the original caliber therefore retaining the immaculate factory machining quality.  The metal finish is 95% and no damage at all except for a few marks on the stock most likely from combat most likely the stock is original to the rifle where as the hand guard is most likely factory new.  I am asking $650 but am open to firearm trades only.  Local pick up only I will not ship it.  Thank you for looking!

title: For Sale/Trade:  BROWNING SA 22  SEMI AUTO .22 TAKEDOWN RIFLE
postcontent:
FOR SELL $400 OR FOR POSSIBLE TRADE ? NOT NEW, BUT NICE SHOOTING SHAPE, LET ME KNOW WHAT YOU HAVE ? SEND PX OR TEXT ME AT REDACTED........................................................................................................................... A living tribute to the genius of Browning. Few autoloading rimfire rifles have endured the test of time and the marketplace like the Browning SA-22. The SA-22 is one of the first autoloading rimfire rifles ever made, and one the most desirable. One John M. Browning’s final designs, his genius shines through in every feature. The slim, forged steel receiver and slender barrel takes down into two compact units without tools. An object of lasting beauty and enjoyment. Though nice to look at, these rifles are meant to be enjoyed in the field as much as they are admired as heirlooms.
If one word were to describe the Semi-Auto 22 it would be "CLASSIC." Like the famous Automatic 5 shotgun or a Hi-Power pistol, the Semi-Auto 22 gives you a real sense of the incredible design skills and genius of John Moses Browning. And the quality of wood and steel will exceed your expectations. People sometimes say "they don't make 'em like they used to." With the Browning Semi-Auto 22, they still do! The Browning 22 Semi-Auto rifle, also known as the Semi Automatic 22 or SA-22, is a takedown rifle produced by FN Herstal based on a John Browning patent. The rifle is currently produced by Browning as the Semi-Auto 22. Production began in 1914 and continued through 1974 in Belgium and production continued in 1976 in Japan by Miroku.[1] It was first exported by FN for the American market in 1956.The SA-22 was the first production semiautomatic .22 rifle] and is regarded as a classic firearm.The Semi-auto .22 is a made from blued steel and walnut, and ejects spent cases downward. This feature was intended by the designer to keep the user's face "protected from gasses and flying particles while firing", at which it succeeds, but also allows the sizzling hot empty case to eject down one's left shirt sleeve, which is memorable, to say the least. The lack of a side-mounted ejection port also leaves a large "canvas" for engraving.[2] Factory engraving was done by hand at FN Herstal, and is done by laser engraving with hand finishing at Miroku.

title: For Sale:  1911 Model 45 Calibre Semi-Auto by Citadel
postcontent:
Have you wanted to own a 1911 model 45 semi-auto like the military uses and could not afford one.  This is a great buy on a very nice weapon that lets you afford a 1911 handgun.  When you hold it then you will know why it was selected by the military as a weapon.  The smooth action of the slide, the easy hammer pull, the rear safety, the perfect hand grips and all at a reasonable weight.

This gun is used but in very good condition with a little holster ware.

The quote below is not about this particular gun, just about the type.
A Qoute from a review on Guns.com 
The Citadel 1911
The Citadel 1911 is manufactured in the Philippines by Armscor and distributed in the states by Legacy. It’s based on the time tested Browning design, single-action recoil operated semi auto, and, same as the original, built to withstand dang near anything.

The barrel, frame and slide are forged steel, and it has a Parkerized, matte black finish. The slide has deep grooves on both the front and rear, and it’s equipped with a skeletonized trigger, hammer, an ambidextrous safety and Walnut grips.
The Citadel 1911 is equipped with Novak style sights and although the sights are not white dot, they are plenty good for my 65 year old eyes.

The barrel has six grooves with a 1 in 16 inch right hand twist and a full length guide rod.

A lowered and flared ejection port helps chunk the empties smoothly.
Performance
After stripping it down and giving a good cleaning I headed for the range. With me, I brought along a selection of ball and hollow point ammo — even some rather old Blazer HP’s I forgot I had.

The first hundred or so rounds I wasn’t even trying for any kind of grouping, I just wanted to check for reliability. Everything fed, and functioned perfectly even the old Blazer rounds.

Next, I set up standard B24 silhouette targets, again at the 7-, 10-, 15- and 25-yard marks and used standard carry rounds, meaning 185 grain JHP’s.

Suffice it to say, this pistol will just chew the center completely out of a B24 target at all four of the yardages mentioned, whether slow or rapid fire. And not once did I have any failure-to-feed or failures-to-eject with any type off ammo.
Final thoughts
It’s now seven months since I purchased this pistol, and I’ve put approximately 3,000 rounds through it. The only things I’ve done are clean it and put a set of Harrison design carry grips on it. It continues to shoot and function perfectly.

I’ve owned a lot of pistols over the years, but only a very select few did I have complete faith and trust in as a carry weapon. The Citadel M1911 is one of them, and I do not make that statement lightly. For the money, I think the Citadel M1911 is hard to beat.

Citadel 1911 Semiautomatic Handguns

Matte Black	5"	
Size 8.87"
Weight 35.5 Oz
Rounds	8

title: For Sale:  Daisy Red Ryder Carbine No. 111 Model 40 - Circa 1947 - 1951
postcontent:
This is a Daisy Red Ryder Carbine No. 111 Model 40.  I date this bb gun from 1947 - 1951.  It has a black painted aluminum cocking lever which means it was made after 1946.  The wooden handgrip dates it before 1952. 

Included in the listing is a Red Ryder lucky coin and Daisy BBs. 

I purchased this gun earlier this year to be used as a painting still life reference. I am a fine artist who works with oil paint in hyperrealism manner.  The painting of the gun can be seen here http://www.kylesurges.com/paintings.html .  Since I have complete the painting I no longer need the gun.       

This Red Ryder is in Good - Fair Condition.  There is a decent amount of wear throughout the gun but overall it doesn't appear to have been abused.  The bluing on the barrel is very apparent and pleasing.  I tried my best to capture all the details in the photos.  There may be a couple nuts missing on the back side but everything is tight and functioning.  At some point, someone added some lock washers to the screws as well.  Another things to mention is the crease or dent in the barrel, the hair line crack on the handgrip, and 3 BB dents on the backside on the stock.   

The gun does shoot very well.  It pretty accurate too.  However, I found that it does seem to shoot a bit to the left.  The cocking lever on this old gun does require some muscle to cock it unlike the new models.  Overall it's a fun gun to shoot a will make a good addition to your collection.  

I also have many more high quality photos of the gun I can email if interested. Please feel free to ask questions.

I prefer a money order from the post office as payment.

title: For Sale:  S&W Model 3906 9MM Matte SS USED
postcontent:
No original Box, 1 magazine and the holster shown in pics is included.

The model 3906 is perhaps the most often overlooked 3rd generation pistol extant. If you do a Google search on it there is precious little information on the net. Even a search here returns fairly little, in comparison to the more talked about models.

Perhaps it is because the 3906 was only produced for around two years. Or the fact that the 3906 is a single stack pistol, containing hardly enough ammunition for a run to the stop & rob to buy milk. Or maybe its because of the 3906's chambering in 9mm which the internet experts tell us is practically insufficient to kill paper targets at the range with. Or perhaps it is because the 3906's all steel construction makes it a little heavy. I understand that lots of folks consider "heavy" pistols negatively these days. Maybe they should lift weights more often.

Yet the 3906 does have a following......small though it may be.

I've often read that one reason for the short production life of the 3906 was the rise in popularity of the high capacity wonder nines. If true, add one more thing to the list of problems those wonder nines caused. I've also read that the 3906 production numbers were alleged to be as low as 2600 pistols. That may account for the scarcity of these guns.

I found out about the existence of the 3906 some years ago. I was intrigued by the prospect of a flat single stack 9mm, like my beloved 3913, with all steel construction. What a great platform for shooting hot 9mm rounds through. Might be the "perfect" do everything well pistol, for me.

It took me quite some time to track one down. The first one I came across was at a gunshow back around 2005.....or 2006. It had adjustable sights. Those looked out of place, to me, on a flat carry/combat pistol. The price was $475 IIRC with only one mag. I thought that was a bit much and passed. I didn't see another 3906 for almost five years. I jumped on that one!

Anyways, the 3906 really is a fine pistol. For just about every purpose. any other fans here?  Hurry, this one will go quick!
__________________

title: For Sale:  Ruger LC9 with Crimson Trace and Accessories
postcontent:
This is a Ruger LC9 with a Crimson Trace laser grip.  This pistol is in great condition, purchased within the last six months, with probably 50-100 rounds fired through it.  The original box and all materials are included.

This pistol includes a total of four magazines and a Kusiac Leather inside the waistband tuckable holster, and a DeSantis Nemesis pocket holster.   It's a great concealed carry package; the size and weight are minimal.  The pistol has a Galloway Precision stainless steel guide rod.

I'm selling for various reasons.  First and foremost, I'm getting married soon (whoo-hooo!).  Also, the LC9s seem to have an issue when loading the first round of our issued hollow-point ammo from a full magazine.  It cycles hollow points fine, but will sometimes hang up when chambering the first round.  This chambering issue hasn't happened at all with round nosed ammo.  Perhaps it just needs broken in, but I don't like the issue.

The Kusiac holster is great.  It has a spare magazine carrier on the front so it's a nice drop-in-the-pants package.  The tan material on the back of the holster is adhesive mole skin that I stuck on for comfort.  It can be removed, though I don't know if it will pull the black finish from the leather.

I'm not interested in trades, sorry.

Additional photos and info by request.

I'll ship from my FFL to yours at your expense.  I'll also do a face to face meeting if you have a concealed weapons permit and are willing to provide a copy and sign a receipt.

The price includes two spare magazines, a magazine loading assist, 100 rounds of ammunition just to get you started, and a soft carry case.
